Cut the @red onion{1} in half through the root, peel and slice into half moon shapes. Cut the @chestnut mushrooms{1} into quarters. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{3%sprigs} and drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can}.

Add @oil{1%tbsp} to a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the onion slices. Cook for ~{5-6%minutes} or until softened and then add in the mushrooms along with @salt{1/4%tsp} and a good grind of @black pepper{} and cook for another ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the @ras-el-hanout{1%tsp} to your #pan{} and cook for a further ~{30%seconds} before adding the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can}. Add the chickpeas to your pan along with the @raisins{1.5%tbsp}. Refill the tomato tin a quarter with @water{1/4%tin}, about @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to a simmer. Leave to cook for ~{8%minutes}.

In the meantime, put @water{300%ml} in a #pot{} with half the @vegetable stock pot{1/2}. Once it comes to a boil, add in the @couscous{3/4%cup}. Cover your pot with a tightly fitting #lid{}, take this off the heat and leave to the side for at least ~{7%minutes} or until the rest of your meal is ready.

When your tagine has been cooking for 8 mins, take your pan off the heat, add the @baby spinach{3%handfuls} to your pan along with two-thirds of the chopped parsley. Stir through and then put a lid on your pan and leave for ~{3-4%minutes} or until the spinach wilts.

When your couscous is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{} and serve with your tagine on top. Scatter the remaining parsley on top. Enjoy!

> Last Christmas, Mimi was camel riding with her family in Morocco! And we can tell you that the tan she had when she got back made us all pretty jealous. Even though Mimi loves a camel ride, the absolute highlight for her was this very tagine, which they ate in the desert under a blanket of twinkling stars and indigo night skies. Now, she couldn't bring back the desert or the skies, but she sure brought back the recipe just for you guys!